   (`{"error":{"code":"internal_error","message":"Something went wrong on
   our end. Please try again shortly."}}`) — the secret did NOT leak, and
   no raw stack trace reached the client. Root cause: Starlette 1.3.1's
   `Starlette.build_middleware_stack` (verified by reading
   `starlette/applications.py` source directly) promotes a handler
   registered for the literal `Exception` class to *also* serve as
   `ServerErrorMiddleware`'s outermost `error_handler`, not only
   `ExceptionMiddleware`'s inner one — so `@app.exception_handler
   (Exception)` in `errors.py` already covers exceptions raised anywhere
   in the user-middleware stack (CSRFGuard/RateLimit/SecurityHeaders/
   SessionIdentity), not just inside routes. This means the actual live
   gap is smaller than described, not larger — a genuine positive
   finding — but errors.py's own docstring ("exceptions raised inside
   ratelimit.py or security.py... never reach ExceptionMiddleware...
   would NOT get the nice JSON error shape... fall through to
   Starlette's built-in ServerErrorMiddleware... returns plain text") is
   factually wrong about the observed behavior on this project's actual
   pinned dependency range (`fastapi>=0.115`, no explicit starlette pin).
   This is a documentation-accuracy finding, not a security bug — flagging
   it back to senior-backend-developer to correct the docstring (either
   confirm this holds across FastAPI's full supported starlette range, or
   narrow the claim), rather than leaving a wrong "known limitation" in
   the code that could cause someone to under-scrutinize a real future
   version bump.

