   (§10.7 CSRF, generalizing the §3A DB-side-effect pattern): both use
   `_seed_decision()` to insert a real `Session` + `Paper` +
   `QueueDecision` row via SQLModel against `db_engine`, sign a real
   session cookie with `app.middleware.session._sign`, send the
   disallowed-origin (and, for PATCH, also non-JSON-Content-Type)
   request against the real `app.main.app`, assert 403/`csrf_rejected`,
   and then **re-query the DB directly** afterward: the PATCH test
   asserts `row.decision == DecisionState.pending` and
   `row.decided_via is None` (unchanged from seed); the DELETE test
   asserts `row.decision == DecisionState.interested` (would have
   flipped to `not_interested` per §4.7 had the handler run). Both are
   genuine side-effect assertions, not merely HTTP-status checks —
   satisfies the same rigor as the original `/search` version of this
   pattern.

5. Zotero-routes coverage decision: CSRFGuardMiddleware is installed as
   plain ASGI middleware ahead of FastAPI's routing/dependency
   injection, so it rejects disallowed-origin/non-JSON requests
   identically regardless of which route or handler sits behind it —
   the mechanism has no route-specific branching that would make
   Zotero's `POST /push` or `DELETE /connection` behave differently at
   the CSRF-guard layer itself. My own prior round already manually
   spot-checked both against the real app and found no discrepancy from
   the /search and /decisions/saved cases. Skipping a *committed*
   DB-side-effect regression test for those two specifically is a
   reasonable, disclosed judgment call given the added
   pyzotero/OAuth-fixture cost and the fact the guard's logic is
   provably route-agnostic — not a correctness gap. Noting for
   completeness only, not as a blocking gap: no test asserts the
   pyzotero client mock was never invoked when a Zotero push is
   rejected (an even cheaper alternative to full DB-side-effect
   assertion for that route specifically) — optional/nice-to-have, not
   required, since the rejection happens before FastAPI ever resolves
   the route's dependencies.

